    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Everyone has one, right?  Their token ForestGul deck with either hobbits or elves...  Truthfully, this was the first deck that I played in the Shadows expansion and I loved it right out of the box.  I have, of course, made some adjustments to it since then.  So, here&#39;s my rendition of the Hobbits/ForestGuls!<br />
<br />
It&#39;s a pretty basic strategy, not too complicated.  Site control on the Freeps side is helpful, but not imperative.  You could bid 1-2 to go first and use your minions to control the site path.  Keeping Gandalf around is more important to the Freeps that the sites.  The sites only help Farmer Maggot; Gandalf aides everyone, especially with the G&#39;s.<br />
<br />
With the Nazgul, site control is quite helpful.  Without the right sites, Nertea and Cantea are fairly neutralized.  Plus, your Lost in the Woods are pointless.  So, use Nelya as your means of getting out your sites.  There are some burden adding mechanics, but it&#39;s not the main focus.   Moreover, you&#39;ll find that it&#39;s more successful at overrunning your opponent&#39;s companions.  Late in the game, you&#39;ll hopefully see 6 or more companions from your opponent.  By that time, you should have out a Drawn or two (ideally all 3) and your Undending Lifes.  The Unendings should make the Nazguls very tough to kill and you&#39;ll be adding burdens once you start popping off companions.<br />
<br />
Again, not a super complicated strategy.  If there were fewer rare, you could almost count this as a beginner deck.  Enjoy!   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
